In this code, `hasOwnProperty('key1')` will return `true` if 'key1' exists in `jsonObject`, and `false` otherwise. Replace 'key1' with the key you want to check.

To convert GeoJSON to KML with folders based on the "Status" attribute, you can use the `togeojson` and `js2xmlparser` libraries. However, these libraries don't support creating folders directly, so you'll need to manually create the KML structure.

Here's a simplified example of how you can do this:

```javascript
const togeojson = require('@mapbox/togeojson');
const js2xmlparser = require('js2xmlparser');
const DOMParser = require('xmldom').DOMParser;

// Convert your data to GeoJSON
let geojson = {
  type: 'FeatureCollection',
  features: adds.map(add => ({
    type: 'Feature',
    geometry: add.geometry,
    properties: add.attributes
  }))
};

// Group features by 'Status'
let groups = {};
geojson.features.forEach(feature => {
  let status = feature.properties.Status;
  if (!groups[status]) {
    groups[status] = {
      type: 'Folder',
      name: status,
      features: []
    };
  }
  groups[status].features.push(feature);
});

// Convert each group to KML
let kml = {
  Document: Object.values(groups).map(group => {
    let folder = {
      Folder: {
        name: group.name,
        Placemark: group.features.map(feature => {
          let kmlFeature = togeojson.kml(new DOMParser().parseFromString(togeojson.gpx.toKml(feature)));
          return kmlFeature.Placemark;
        })
      }
    };
    return folder;
  })
};

// Convert the KML object to XML
let xml = js2xmlparser.parse('kml', kml, {format: true});

console.log(xml);
```

This script first converts your data to GeoJSON, then groups the features by the "Status" attribute. For each group, it creates a KML Folder and converts each feature to a KML Placemark. Finally, it converts the KML object to XML.

Please note that this is a simplified example and might not work perfectly with your data. You might need to adjust it to fit your needs.

To create KML folders beforehand and allocate each feature to the corresponding folder, you can modify the previous script as follows:

```javascript
const togeojson = require('@mapbox/togeojson');
const js2xmlparser = require('js2xmlparser');
const DOMParser = require('xmldom').DOMParser;

// Convert your data to GeoJSON
let geojson = {
  type: 'FeatureCollection',
  features: adds.map(add => ({
    type: 'Feature',
    geometry: add.geometry,
    properties: add.attributes
  }))
};

// Define your folders
let folders = {
  'MSD': [],
  'AnotherStatus': [],
  // Add more folders as needed
};

// Allocate features to the corresponding folder
geojson.features.forEach(feature => {
  let status = feature.properties.Status;
  if (folders.hasOwnProperty(status)) {
    folders[status].push(feature);
  }
});

// Convert each folder to KML
let kml = {
  Document: Object.keys(folders).map(status => {
    let folder = {
      Folder: {
        name: status,
        Placemark: folders[status].map(feature => {
          let kmlFeature = togeojson.kml(new DOMParser().parseFromString(togeojson.gpx.toKml(feature)));
          return kmlFeature.Placemark;
        })
      }
    };
    return folder;
  })
};

// Convert the KML object to XML
let xml = js2xmlparser.parse('kml', kml, {format: true});

console.log(xml);
```

In this script, you first define your folders based on the possible values of the "Status" attribute. Then, you allocate each feature to the corresponding folder based on its "Status". Finally, you convert each folder to KML and the KML object to XML.

Please note that this script assumes that the "Status" attribute of each feature matches one of the predefined folders. If a feature has a "Status" that doesn't match any folder, it will be ignored. You might need to adjust this behavior to fit your needs.

