Sure, you can create a function that sets the password reset token and expiration time for a given user. Here's how you can do it:

```javascript
async function setResetToken(userId, token) {
  const db = await database.connect();
  const user = await db.collection('users').findOne({ userId });

  if (!user) {
    throw new Error('User not found!');
  }

  // Set the password reset token and expiration time
  user.resetPasswordToken = token;
  user.resetPasswordExpires = Date.now() + 3600000; // 1 hour

  const result = await db.collection('users').updateOne({ userId }, { $set: user });

  if (result.modifiedCount !== 1) {
    throw new Error('Failed to set reset token!');
  }

  return true;
}
```

In this function, `userId` is the ID of the user and `token` is the password reset token. The function first finds the user with the given ID. If the user is found, it sets the `resetPasswordToken` and `resetPasswordExpires` fields and updates the user in the database. If the update is successful, the function returns `true`. If the user is not found or the update fails, the function throws an error.

