Yes, you can combine multiple FeatureLayers in ArcGIS API for JavaScript, which I assume you're using given the context. However, the way you combine them depends on what you want to achieve.

If you want to display multiple FeatureLayers on a map, you can simply add multiple FeatureLayers to the map's layers:

```javascript
let featureLayer1 = new FeatureLayer({
  url: "https://services.arcgis.com/V6ZHFr6zdgNZuVG0/arcgis/rest/services/Landscape_Trees/FeatureServer/0"
});

let featureLayer2 = new FeatureLayer({
  url: "https://services.arcgis.com/V6ZHFr6zdgNZuVG0/arcgis/rest/services/US_Senators/FeatureServer/0"
});

let map = new Map({
  basemap: "streets",
  layers: [featureLayer1, featureLayer2]  // Add multiple FeatureLayers here
});

let view = new MapView({
  container: "viewDiv",
  map: map
});
```

If you want to combine the data from multiple FeatureLayers into a single layer, you'll need to use the `queryFeatures` method of each FeatureLayer to get the data, and then combine the data manually. However, please note that this can be complex and may not work well if the FeatureLayers have different schemas.

If you provide more details about what you want to achieve, I can give a more specific answer.

To display multiple FeatureLayers in the same FeatureTable based on a selection from a combobox, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a state variable to hold the current FeatureLayer.
2. When the combobox selection changes, update the current FeatureLayer state variable.
3. Pass the current FeatureLayer to the FeatureTable.

Here's a simplified example:

```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { FeatureLayer, FeatureTable } from 'esri';

function MyComponent() {
  const [currentLayer, setCurrentLayer] = useState(null);

  const handleComboboxChange = (event) => {
    const layerUrl = event.target.value;
    setCurrentLayer(new FeatureLayer({ url: layerUrl }));
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <select onChange={handleComboboxChange}>
        <option value="https://services.arcgis.com/V6ZHFr6zdgNZuVG0/arcgis/rest/services/Landscape_Trees/FeatureServer/0">Layer 1</option>
        <option value="https://services.arcgis.com/V6ZHFr6zdgNZuVG0/arcgis/rest/services/US_Senators/FeatureServer/0">Layer 2</option>
      </select>

      {currentLayer && <FeatureTable featureLayer={currentLayer} />}
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this code, `handleComboboxChange` is called when the combobox selection changes. It creates a new FeatureLayer with the selected URL and sets it as the current layer. The FeatureTable then displays the current layer.

Please note that this is a simplified example and may not work as-is. You'll need to adapt it to your actual code and the library you're using. If you're not using a library that provides a `FeatureTable` component, you'll need to create the FeatureTable manually using the ArcGIS API for JavaScript.

Yes, you can display different FeatureLayers in the same FeatureTable by changing the `featureLayer` property of the FeatureTable. 

When the selection in the combobox changes, you can create a new FeatureLayer with the selected URL and set it as the `featureLayer` of the FeatureTable. 

Here's a simplified example of how you can do this:

```javascript
import { useRef, useState } from 'react';
import { loadModules } from 'esri-loader';

function MyComponent() {
  const tableDiv = useRef(null);
  const [table, setTable] = useState(null);

  const handleComboboxChange = async (event) => {
    const layerUrl = event.target.value;

    const [FeatureLayer, FeatureTable] = await loadModules([
      'esri/layers/FeatureLayer',
      'esri/widgets/FeatureTable'
    ]);

    const featureLayer = new FeatureLayer({ url: layerUrl });

    if (table) {
      table.layer = featureLayer;
    } else {
      const featureTable = new FeatureTable({
        container: tableDiv.current,
        layer: featureLayer
      });

      setTable(featureTable);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <select onChange={handleComboboxChange}>
        <option value="https://services.arcgis.com/V6ZHFr6zdgNZuVG0/arcgis/rest/services/Landscape_Trees/FeatureServer/0">Layer 1</option>
        <option value="https://services.arcgis.com/V6ZHFr6zdgNZuVG0/arcgis/rest/services/US_Senators/FeatureServer/0">Layer 2</option>
      </select>

      <div ref={tableDiv}></div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this code, `handleComboboxChange` is called when the combobox selection changes. It creates a new FeatureLayer with the selected URL and sets it as the `layer` of the FeatureTable. If the FeatureTable doesn't exist yet, it creates a new FeatureTable.

Please note that this is a simplified example and may not work as-is. You'll need to adapt it to your actual code and the library you're using. If you're not using a library that provides a `FeatureTable` component, you'll need to create the FeatureTable manually using the ArcGIS API for JavaScript.

