The error message `TypeError: source.on is not a function` is typically thrown when you're trying to use a function on an object that doesn't have that function. In this case, it seems like the `request` module is trying to call the `on` function on an object, but it's not a function.

This error is often caused by passing an incorrect type of argument to a function that expects a stream. In your case, it seems to be happening in the `generateTokenGIS` function when you're making a request to the ArcGIS API.

The `request` function from the `request` module expects a stream when you're sending data in the request body, but it seems like you're passing an object (`jsonData`) instead.

Here's how you can modify the `generateTokenGIS` function to fix this issue:

```javascript
function generateTokenGIS(User) {
  let jsonData = User;
  jsonData.f = 'json';
  jsonData.client = 'referer';
  jsonData.referer = 'arcgis.com';
  jsonData.expiration = '1';

  var options = {
    'method': 'POST',
    'url': 'https://www.arcgis.com/sharing/rest/generateToken',
    'headers': {
      'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'
    },
    form: jsonData
  };

  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    request(options, function (error, response, body) {
      if (error) reject(error);
      else resolve(JSON.parse(body));
    });
  });
}
```

In this code, I've changed `formData` to `form` and the `Content-Type` header to `'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'`. This is because the ArcGIS API expects the data to be sent as form data, not JSON.

I've also wrapped the `request` function in a promise so that it can be used with `await` in the `doLogin` function. The promise resolves with the parsed response body when the request is successful, and rejects with the error when the request fails.

