If you're using Express.js within a React application, it's likely you're using it to create an API or server-side rendered pages. This setup is often referred to as a full-stack application.

In development, you can use `npm start` to run your React application and another command (like `node server.js` or `nodemon server.js`) to run your Express server. They will typically run on different ports (like 3000 for React and 5000 for Express).

For production, you need to build your React application using `npm run build`, which creates a `build` directory with static files. You can then serve these static files from your Express server.

Here's a basic example of how you can serve your React application from an Express server:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const path = require('path');
const app = express();

// Serve static files from the React app
app.use(express.static(path.join(__dirname, 'build')));

// The "catchall" handler: for any request that doesn't
// match one above, send back React's index.html file.
app.get('*', (req, res) => {
  res.sendFile(path.join(__dirname, 'build', 'index.html'));
});

const port = process.env.PORT || 5000;
app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server is listening on port ${port}`);
});
```

In this example, any request that doesn't match a specific route will send back the `index.html` file, which is the entry point to your React application.

Remember to replace `'build'` with the actual path to your React application's build directory. This setup should work equally well in both development and production environments.

